My new year is off to a slow start. I had big plans to get back to my previous levels of climbing, running, strength training, and yoga. But my defibrillator had other plans and delivered a shock to my heart on December 30, 2022. It turns out that the shock was delivered in error. My abnormal heart rhythm was double counted at 200bpm when my heart rate was at only 100bpm. I don’t want to shock my heart again so I am currently trying to keep my heart rate below 100. This means no running or climbing. And I have to be very careful when working out or doing yoga. My activities are limited at best. Non-existent at worst.

The next step is to try to reprogram the defibrillator to account for my specific heart rhythm. But there are no guarantees that this will work. My cardiologists strongly advise against turning the defibrillator off or taking it out. My congenital heart condition and childhood surgery put me at moderate risk for life threatening cardiac events like the sustained ventricular tachycardia that experienced four times throughout 2022.

For now, my heart seems to be doing well. My body is ready to get back to full activity. But the technology is giving me some trouble. I have to be patient for just a little longer.

Slide 2 and 3 are the Edwards Sapien 3 Transcatheter Pulmonary Valve System and Alterra Adaptive Present that were implanted in my heart in late December 2022.
#prasaritapadottanasana #widelegforwardfold #widelegforwardbend #yogaposes #yogaasana #yogateacher #yogainstructions #howtoyoga #onlineyoga #yogaonline #yogaalignment

My fitness journey seems to be back on track. After 8 months of limited activity, 4 sustained ventricular tachycardia events, 7 defibrillator shocks, 3 heart procedures, and countless cardiology appointments, my heart is finally back to “normal” AND my defibrillator is working properly.

Yesterday was the first day in 8 months that I was able to get my heart rate up to 150 without a cardiac event or defibrillator shock. It was only for short intervals but it felt good. I’ll try running next, then climbing. My plan is to ease into each activity as I test my heart and the device.

I’m looking forward to an amazing 2023!

#Goalofnewyou - Day 1 - Talking to and about yourself with love

I love being in pigeon pose (prep) in a yoga class because it is usually an opportunity to pause and soften in the practice. It is a pose that is generally held longer and I have time to think and reflect. For me, it is a pose in which I would love to continue to improve but I remind myself to accept where I am today and love who I am in the moment.

Talking to and about myself with love does not come naturally to me. But yoga gives me the opportunity to develop the language of self love. If I can be kind and loving towards my practice, pose, and body on the yoga mat, then maybe I can be more loving towards myself off of the yoga mat too.

#goALOfnewyou - Day 2 - Giving yourself a break from self-judgement.

Hanumanasana (Hanuman pose or “splits”) is not my favorite pose. As I look at my pose, I see that my front leg is not completely straight, my back leg is slightly turned out, my hips are turning open to one side, my upper body is leaning forward, my head is shifted forward, and my hips are not very close to the ground. I see many different ways that the pose could be improved. This self-judgement IS helpful in analyzing the pose and determining what needs to be done to improve it. HOWEVER, when I pause, take a breath, soften, relax a little, and take a break from self-judgement, I feel the amazing stretch and remember how far I’ve come in this pose. And then, I enjoy the pose a little more. I’m not stopping all self-judgement forever. But taking a little break helps me to enjoy the process and stay on the path.

#GoALOfnewyou - Day 3 - Prioritizing yourself.

I have a congenital heart defect that was repaired via open heart surgery when I was six years old. Last spring, the scar tissue from that surgery caused a life-threatening cardiac event. All of my doctors tell me that being in excellent physical shape is what delayed the event until now (47 years later) and may have even saved my life. Thank goodness that physical fitness and personal health have been a priority all of my life.

I had three cardiac procedures in 2022 and one more scheduled for 2023. Taking care of my heart and my general health continue to be a priority. This means occasionally saying “no” to work, family, and friends and more often saying “yes” to healthy choices and actions. It mean putting my own health first.

#goALofnewyou - Day 4 - Trusting yourself.

I have learned to trust myself by challenging myself physically, mentally, emotionally, and spiritually. When I test my limits, I learn what is possible and realize that I have the strength and endurance to overcome the most challenging obstacles. In my yoga practice, handstands have been a great test of trust in myself.

My heart seems to have settled down. No more procedures for the foreseeable future. I’m back to most of my normal activities, including running, climbing, weight training, and yoga. I have not had a cardiac event in over 5 months. My new valve is working great. I feel good.

Time to get back to inversions, arm balances, and backbends. My intention is to get back to where I was one year ago and then continue to expand. I’m starting simple in the more familiar poses. This has always been one of my favorites.

I mentioned in a previous post that I am back to my normal activities after a challenging year of cardiac events and subsequent corrective procedures. What I failed to mention is that I still sometimes get a little nervous when my heart rate elevates or I feel an abnormal rhythm. I have gone back to the activities that I love but not without some stress or worry. Also, I have NOT gone back to drinking alcohol or caffeine. Even eating too much sugar makes me nervous, so I’m more careful now. 

As my body and heart get stronger, my mind seems to be following. I hope to get to a point where I have the confidence to go all out in whatever activity I am participating in, without any fear of my heart causing problems. I’m not there yet, but it gets a little better every day.

I was a Certified Anusara Yoga Teacher up until a few years ago. My current practice and teaching style are both strongly influenced by the Anusara method. It really works for me and I love it.

Twenty years ago, the founder of Anusara Yoga used to come up with new pose variations that would ripple throughout the Anusara community. But I did not feel like I was encouraged to explore and create in the same way.

Today, thanks to the Instagram yoga community, I feel much more free to explore the boundaries and limitations of yoga poses and truly expand beyond. In the past, I would never have found myself in a headstand like this. There would be no reason for it. It is not a classic yoga pose and it would not have been something handed down to the Anusara community from one of its leaders. Instagram has inspired us to move beyond classic yoga poses and explore the infinite possibilities of what the human body can do.

One year has passed since I ended up in the hospital with ventricular tachycardia. I have been in and out of hospitals and cardiology offices since then. At one point, I almost gave up, thinking that my life had changed forever and that I would have to give up many of the things that I love, including yoga, climbing, running, swimming, and weight training. But fortunately, I found the amazing Adult Congenital Heart Disease (ACHD) team at Cedar’s Sinai. They “rewired” the electrical system of my heart and gave me a new pulmonary valve and now my heart is better than ever! But my life has changed even though I haven’t given up any of my physical activities. I have NOT had any alcohol or caffeine in the past year. I may go back to drinking coffee someday, but I am done drinking alcohol. I also cannot use infrared saunas or go through metal detectors because of an implanted defibrillator. Life has changed. But life is good.

Earlier this week, I was climbing at The Post Climbing Gym. I finished sending a slab V3 and was sitting watching someone else climb the same problem. My heart felt weird and I started recording an ECG on my Apple Watch. I immediately recognized the pattern as ventricular tachycardia (VT). I knew I would receive a shock from my S-ICD (subcutaneous implanted cardiac defibrillator) within 30 seconds. I laid down and was shocked by the device. My heart was still in VT for another 20 seconds. I thought I might get a second shock but my heart found its way back to a sinus rhythm on its own. All of this was confirmed by the data recorded by my device.

I receive a shock from my defibrillator (I call it “Quato”) when my heart rate is (a) above 200 bpm, (b) for more than 30 seconds, and (c) shows a VT pattern (see first image).

I have already talked to my Electro Cardiologist. He is going to do an electrophysiology study of my heart and replace my S-ICD with a pacemaker/defibrillator combo in the new year. The new device will attempt to pace me out of VT before delivering a shock. 

The second slide was recorded this morning. My heart was in VT for a few seconds, but not long enough to warrant a shock. The third slide is my normal sinus rhythm.

#tetraologyoffallot #tetraologyoffallotrepair #ventriculartachycardia #sicd #chdwarrior #heartpatient #firstworldproblems

My heart has gone into ventricular tachycardia twice while climbing. Both times I had just finished climbing V3 problems, which are not the most challenging for me. I am generally comfortable on V4s. I find V5s very challenging. 

I do not think it is the exertion or the intensity of the climb that triggers the cardiac event. I think it is the fear factor and the adrenaline that triggers my heart. This problem/climb is a pretty good example. It is not the most strenuous climb, but it is a little spooky. My heart was pounding while stemming my way up these tiny white holds.  This was a V6! It will likely be my last V6 for a long time.
